  (24, 'B', 'Include a full roof inspection, not just the leak area', TRUE, 'Leak-source rule. Reference: Chapter 11, Module 2.', 2),
  (24, 'C', 'Skip the inspection and quote a patch', FALSE, 'Skipping inspection causes the wrong-location patch problem.', 3),
  (24, 'D', 'Wait for the customer to identify the source', FALSE, 'Customers don''t typically identify sources; that''s the rep''s job.', 4),
  (25, 'A', 'Replacing all hands-on inspection', FALSE, 'Drones supplement, not replace, hands-on inspection.', 1),
  (25, 'B', 'Multi-story buildings, tile roofs, and complex geometries where walking is risky', TRUE, 'Drone supplements but does not replace hands-on inspection. Reference: Chapter 12, Module 7.', 2),
  (25, 'C', 'Single-family residential only', FALSE, 'Drones are valuable across building types.', 3),
  (25, 'D', 'Inspecting attics', FALSE, 'Drones don''t access attics.', 4),
  (26, 'A', 'Skipping the ponding inspection until rain', FALSE, 'Ponding evidence is documentable on dry days.', 1),
  (26, 'B', 'Using chalk to outline the extent marked by dirt rings, then photographing', TRUE, 'Standard ponding documentation. Reference: Chapter 16, Module 7.', 2),
  (26, 'C', 'Estimating the ponding from satellite photos', FALSE, 'On-roof documentation is required.', 3),
  (26, 'D', 'Asking the customer to verify', FALSE, 'Customer verification supplements but doesn''t replace direct documentation.', 4),
  (27, 'A', 'Quote the price on the spot to close the deal', FALSE, 'Verbal pricing creates anchor problems and inaccuracies.', 1),
  (27, 'B', 'Decline to inspect further until pricing is settled', FALSE, 'Inspection precedes pricing, not the reverse.', 2),
  (27, 'C', 'Defer to the written proposal so the scope and price match what''s actually on the roof', TRUE, 'Honest framework. Reference: Chapter 12, Module 11.', 3),
  (27, 'D', 'Quote a high price to anchor the negotiation', FALSE, 'Anchoring is a pressure tactic.', 4),
  (28, 'A', 'Visible roof surface conditions', FALSE, 'Reps may document visible conditions.', 1),
  (28, 'B', 'Customer-reported information (clearly attributed)', FALSE, 'Reps may document customer reports when clearly attributed.', 2),
  (28, 'C', 'Severity ratings using the four-point scale', FALSE, 'Reps apply severity ratings.', 3),
  (28, 'D', 'Structural failure, hail damage for insurance, or mold identification', TRUE, 'These exceed rep authorization. Reference: Chapter 12, Module 6.', 4),
  (29, 'A', 'Climbing the ladder', FALSE, 'Pre-inspection conversation comes first.', 1),
  (29, 'B', 'Asking lead-qualification questions before inspection', TRUE, 'Standard inspection sequence. Reference: Chapter 12.', 2),
  (29, 'C', 'Drone deployment', FALSE, 'Drone use is a method choice, not the first step.', 3),
  (29, 'D', 'Quoting a price', FALSE, 'Pricing comes after inspection and proposal preparation.', 4),
  (30, 'A', 'Sits directly above the visible interior damage', FALSE, 'Water travels along structure before showing inside.', 1),
  (30, 'B', 'Sits on the opposite side of the roof from the damage', FALSE, 'Not the typical pattern.', 2),
  (30, 'C', 'Travels along structure, conduit, or substrate before showing inside — rarely directly above interior damage', TRUE, 'Leak-source rule. Reference: Chapter 11, Module 2.', 3),
  (30, 'D', 'Cannot be identified by inspection', FALSE, 'Often identifiable through thorough inspection.', 4),
  (31, 'A', 'Walk the roof carefully despite conditions', FALSE, 'Wet or windy tile roofs are unsafe to walk.', 1),
  (31, 'B', 'Skip the inspection entirely', FALSE, 'Inspection is still possible with alternative methods.', 2),
  (31, 'C', 'Use a combination of ground-level walk-around, drone (if conditions permit), and ladder-edge — and reschedule the roof walk if conditions don''t support it', TRUE, 'Safe and thorough approach. Reference: Chapter 12.', 3),
  (31, 'D', 'Tell the customer their roof is fine', FALSE, 'Pronouncing condition without inspection is dishonest.', 4),
  (32, 'A', 'Patch the area directly above the interior damage', FALSE, 'Patching the wrong location is the textbook leak-call mistake.', 1),
  (32, 'B', 'Charge for the inspection and leave without patching', FALSE, 'Better to escalate than abandon the customer.', 2),
  (32, 'C', 'Escalate to senior estimator or qualified inspector for further investigation; communicate honestly with the customer', TRUE, 'Honest response when source can''t be identified. Reference: Module 2.', 3),
  (32, 'D', 'Recommend full replacement to be safe', FALSE, 'Recommending replacement without inspection support is overselling.', 4),
  (33, 'A', 'Address it anyway to be helpful', FALSE, 'Exceeding authorization creates problems.', 1),
  (33, 'B', 'Ignore it and complete the maintenance scope only', FALSE, 'Ignoring urgent conditions is unprofessional.', 2),
  (33, 'C', 'Document the condition, escalate, and communicate the finding to the customer', TRUE, 'Standard escalation pattern. Reference: Chapter 11, Chapter 12.', 3),
  (33, 'D', 'Quote a price on the spot', FALSE, 'Pricing follows scope, not the reverse.', 4),
  (34, 'A', 'Skip the documentation and provide a verbal price', FALSE, 'Skipping documentation creates downstream problems.', 1),
  (34, 'B', 'Explain that the documentation protects them in the future for warranty, insurance, and resale, and that the price will be accurate because the scope is real', TRUE, 'Honest framing from Module 7. Reference: Module 7, Chapter 12.', 2),
  (34, 'C', 'Apologize and reduce the inspection scope', FALSE, 'Reducing scope to placate the customer creates problems.', 3),
  (34, 'D', 'Bill the customer for the documentation time', FALSE, 'Documentation is part of standard inspection scope.', 4),
  (35, 'A', 'The coating chemistry is more important than the substrate', FALSE, 'Substrate matters more than coating chemistry for future work.', 1),
  (35, 'B', 'The substrate determines future scope options for repair, restoration, and replacement', TRUE, 'Substrate matters more than coating chemistry for future work. Reference: Chapter 17.', 2),
  (35, 'C', 'Coatings always last longer than substrates', FALSE, 'Coatings extend substrate life but the substrate is what matters.', 3),
  (35, 'D', 'The warranty depends only on the coating', FALSE, 'Warranty depends on coating but substrate matters for future scope.', 4),
  (36, 'A', 'Adding a continuous waterproof layer to an aged roof', FALSE, 'That describes restoration.', 1),
  (36, 'B', 'Removing the existing roof and installing a new one', FALSE, 'That describes replacement.', 2),
  (36, 'C', 'Addressing a specific failure on a roof that otherwise has remaining service life', TRUE, 'Standard definition. Reference: Chapter 13.', 3),
  (36, 'D', 'Annual maintenance work', FALSE, 'Maintenance is broader than repair.', 4),
  (37, 'A', 'Targeted patching of a single failure', FALSE, 'That describes repair.', 1),
  (37, 'B', 'Adding waterproofing, performance, or service life to an aged but sound substrate', TRUE, 'Standard definition. Reference: Chapter 13.', 2),
  (37, 'C', 'Tearing off the existing roof and starting over', FALSE, 'That describes replacement.', 3),
  (37, 'D', 'The same as roof painting', FALSE, 'Coatings aren''t paint.', 4),
  (38, 'A', 'Removing the existing roof down to the deck', FALSE, 'That describes tear-off.', 1),
  (38, 'B', 'Installing a new roof system over the existing one, where code permits and the substrate qualifies', TRUE, 'Standard definition. Reference: Chapter 13.', 2),
  (38, 'C', 'Repairing only the leaks', FALSE, 'That describes repair.', 3),
  (38, 'D', 'Annual maintenance', FALSE, 'Maintenance isn''t recover.', 4),
  (39, 'A', 'Light surface dirt', FALSE, 'Surface dirt is addressable through prep.', 1),
  (39, 'B', 'Wet insulation, severe ponding, or widespread substrate failure', TRUE, 'Cross-system disqualifiers. Reference: Chapter 13, Table 6.', 2),
  (39, 'C', 'A single failed pipe boot', FALSE, 'Localized failures are addressable in prep.', 3),
  (39, 'D', 'Biological staining on the north slope', FALSE, 'Treatable; not disqualifying.', 4),
  (40, 'A', 'Cost, customer, condition, closing', FALSE, 'Not the standard framework.', 1),
  (40, 'B', 'Condition, customer fit, budget, honest-versus-easy', TRUE, 'Four lenses in order. Reference: Chapter 13.', 2),
  (40, 'C', 'Budget, condition, paperwork, warranty', FALSE, 'Not the standard framework.', 3),
  (40, 'D', 'Customer, condition, customer, condition', FALSE, 'Not the standard framework.', 4)
